cs.DS, cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.LG. 

The paper deals with algorithms for graph problems, specifically the replacement-paths problem, and introduces a new concept of concise matrices. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves computational geometry (cs.CG) as it deals with planar graphs and minor-closed graphs. The use of matrices and linear algebra suggests that the paper may also belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the paper's focus on algorithmic efficiency and time complexity suggests that it may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning).
